The lowest price for the software is a whopping $209.91/yr and the highest is $449.94/yr (and those are the sale prices!) which may be pricey for a person who can't afford that right now. I get it. You want business, which is why you use this course as a lead magnet. If you want to teach a course using the software be more transparent and PUT THAT IN YOUR TITLE like, "How To Make A Profit Dropshipping on Ebay Using Zik Analytics Subscription, or something like that.  Any use this software may have had was lost on me with the shameful tactics - like endless 50% off coupon that was constantly and irritatingly popping up every 30 seconds or so in his "lessons."

A very good basic tutorial that covers all the bases well.  There is a lot of information for grabs and you may need to revisit these videos if you intend to learn more than of the mentioned languages and use VS Code as your IDE.  It covers the installation of VS Code on three distinct platforms, and the installation of Python, Java, MinGW, node.js and GO languages on Windows with relative ease.  It also helps you to install the necessary extensions to run these languages on VS Code.

However, just a few things that need the author(s) might consider if they plan to improve on the course:
1. The installation process of VS Code on Windows is covered in three other videos outside of Section 2.  Six minutes may not mean much, but if you have covered it before, why repeat and bore the listeners?
2. The use of software and the related extension is described well, but it does not cover why we need the language library as well as extensions, or why we configure environmental variables.
Super simple to understand and good examples shown along with the techniques to be used.

content:
I was very opposed to using Tailwind before watching this course. I've been writing custom css since the early 2000's - I know it well. Frameworks/libraries have always been bloated and fight my fast development of custom designs. This course helped change my mind- and in only 2 hours!!!

 Dary explains only the main things needed by most sites and gives the logic behind the way classes are labeled. This makes it very easy to learn since instead of trying to memorize abstract labels, you realize they relate to the visual result you're trying to achieve. Also, he shows the tailwind docs and shows how the tailwind class name relates to its "longhand" manual css properties.

Only comments for improvement: lecture 12 customizing - I wish Dary had spent more time on how to customize colors - this portion seemed very rushed. Additionally, it would have been nice to have an assignment/project where we were given specific instructions on the visual look of a 1 page site, and then have him show his coding of that solution - it would help cement the content. All in all, still, a GREAT COURSE!
